{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[step]] or [[climb]] onto or otherwise [[enter]] a [[ship]], [[aircraft]], [[train]] or other [[conveyance]].
#: ''It is time to '''board''' the aircraft.''
#* Totten
#*: You '''board''' an enemy to capture her, and a stranger to receive news or make a communication.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[provide]] someone with meals and lodging, usually in [[exchange]] for [[money]].
#: ''to '''board''' one's horse at a livery stable''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[receive]] meals and lodging in exchange for money.
#* ''Spectator''
#*: We {{...}} '''board''' in the same house.
# {{context|transitive|nautical|lang=en}} To [[capture]] an [[enemy]] ship by going [[alongside]] and [[grappling]] her, then [[invading]] her with a [[boarding party]]
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[obtain]] meals, or meals and [[lodging]]s, [[statedly]] for compensation
# {{context|transitive|now|_|rare|lang=en}} To [[approach]] (someone); to make advances to, [[accost]].
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', II.iv:
#*: Ere long with like againe he '''boorded''' mee, / Saying, he now had boulted all the floure {{...}}
# To cover with boards or boarding.
#: ''to '''board''' a house''
#* Cowper
#*: the '''boarded''' hovel
# To hit (someone) with a wooden board.

